WEBVTT

00:01.310 --> 00:02.034
[train horn blows]

00:02.068 --> 00:04.517
[gentle piano music]

00:04.551 --> 00:06.931
- How do we make a show that looks completely different

00:06.965 --> 00:08.482
than the show
we did last week?

00:08.517 --> 00:10.586
[rousing orchestral music]

00:10.620 --> 00:14.034
It's nice if you really,
really liked last week's show,

00:14.068 --> 00:16.827
but I'm not going
to do that one again.

00:16.862 --> 00:19.862
Certainty is my enemy.
You know, I'm all about doubt.

00:19.896 --> 00:21.551
[lightning cracks]

00:21.586 --> 00:23.068
[cheering]

00:23.103 --> 00:25.862
I started doing this
late in life.

00:25.896 --> 00:29.655
I can't say that
I'm evolving or maturing

00:29.689 --> 00:32.172
or doing anything differently.

00:32.206 --> 00:35.344
[laughs]
Same dick I was 13 years ago.

00:35.379 --> 00:37.172
[upbeat rock music]

00:37.206 --> 00:38.862
both: ♪ I took a walk
through this ♪

00:38.896 --> 00:42.241
♪ Beautiful world

00:42.275 --> 00:47.137
♪ Felt the cool rain
on my shoulder ♪

00:47.172 --> 00:50.724
♪ Found something good
in this ♪

00:50.758 --> 00:53.413
♪ Beautiful world

00:53.448 --> 00:59.206
♪ I felt the rain
getting colder ♪

00:59.241 --> 01:02.758
- ♪ La, la
- ♪ Sha la, la, la, la

01:02.793 --> 01:04.586
♪ Sha la, la, la, la

01:04.620 --> 01:08.758
- ♪ Sha la, la, la
- Sha la, la, la, la ♪

01:08.793 --> 01:13.689
♪ Sha la, la, la, la, la

01:15.275 --> 01:17.137
- What do you think he did,
I mean,

01:17.172 --> 01:19.827
in terms of
the impact on television?

01:19.862 --> 01:21.482
- Yeah.
- It's so multifaceted, so--

01:21.517 --> 01:23.310
- Sure.

01:23.344 --> 01:26.379
I think that prior to Tony
on television,

01:26.413 --> 01:30.931
food TV, such as it was,
and travel TV, such as it was,

01:30.965 --> 01:33.379
were both essentially
serviced-based.

01:33.413 --> 01:35.000
It was very top-down.

01:35.034 --> 01:36.862
There's an expert
showing you what to do

01:36.896 --> 01:38.344
when you're in
an unfamiliar situation.

01:38.379 --> 01:40.344
"I don't know how to make this."
Here's how you do it.

01:40.379 --> 01:42.241
"I don't know what to do
when I'm there."

01:42.275 --> 01:45.034
Here's what you do.
Here's what everybody does.

01:45.068 --> 01:47.482
What I wished for often
was specificity.

01:47.517 --> 01:50.068
Take me to a place.
Show me that real place.

01:50.103 --> 01:51.482
Show me what motivates people.

01:51.517 --> 01:54.413
[rock music]

01:54.448 --> 01:59.724
♪

01:59.758 --> 02:01.241
- You did travel with him.

02:01.275 --> 02:04.137
You were sitting in your couch
in your home,

02:04.172 --> 02:06.310
but you were with him
wherever he went.

02:06.344 --> 02:08.862
- He would be overseas
in the Far East one week

02:08.896 --> 02:10.413
and then maybe in the Bronx,

02:10.448 --> 02:13.413
you know, the next week,
or in Miami the next week.

02:13.448 --> 02:17.517
- He wasn't worried about
protecting a boxed image

02:17.551 --> 02:19.551
of who he was, right?

02:19.586 --> 02:21.827
It was like, "I'm gonna put
myself in this experience,

02:21.862 --> 02:23.586
and it's gonna be what it is."

02:23.620 --> 02:26.482
- I perceived him a little bit
like Indiana Jones.

02:26.517 --> 02:30.586
He could be on the road
in a T-shirt having a beer

02:30.620 --> 02:33.551
or in a kitchen
talking to the line cooks.

02:33.586 --> 02:35.827
And then he could come home
and put on a suit and tie

02:35.862 --> 02:38.655
and be a man about town
giving a tribute speech

02:38.689 --> 02:40.000
to his publisher.

02:40.034 --> 02:41.862
You know, he cleaned up good,

02:41.896 --> 02:45.172
but he was also really
comfortable out in the wild.

02:45.206 --> 02:48.034
- You see a man step foot
into the world

02:48.068 --> 02:50.206
kind of shaky at first,
kind of unsure,

02:50.241 --> 02:52.586
increasing in confidence
in who he is

02:52.620 --> 02:56.241
as he's buffeted by a larger
world full of doubt,

02:56.275 --> 02:58.172
full of ambiguity,
full of questions,

02:58.206 --> 03:00.896
full of unknowable things
and react accordingly.

03:02.551 --> 03:05.344
[engine revving]

03:12.034 --> 03:13.517
- I would describe myself as

03:13.551 --> 03:16.068
a lucky cook who
gets to tell stories.

03:16.103 --> 03:21.724
And I think any other--
I'm certainly not a journalist.

03:21.758 --> 03:24.586
I'm not a chef anymore.

03:24.620 --> 03:27.206
I'd like to flatter myself
by saying I'm an essayist,

03:27.241 --> 03:30.862
but I'm a storyteller.

03:30.896 --> 03:35.206
I see stuff.
I talk about that.

03:35.241 --> 03:37.344
I talk about how it made me
feel at the time.

03:37.379 --> 03:39.379
I think that's the best--
if you can do that honestly,

03:39.413 --> 03:42.172
that's about the best
you could hope for I think.

03:42.551 --> 03:46.551
[sitar music]

03:46.586 --> 03:48.827
I--I don't feel I'm capable
of going back and having

03:48.862 --> 03:51.034
an intelligent conversation
about my experience.

03:51.068 --> 03:52.896
I feel all messed up
emotionally.

03:52.931 --> 03:55.379
- But then I think this means
that you truly came here,

03:55.413 --> 03:57.068
because when you get close to
something you understand

03:57.103 --> 03:58.827
that you don't understand
what's going on.

03:58.862 --> 04:00.206
When you're far from it,

04:00.241 --> 04:02.068
it seems kind of
solvable and simple.

04:02.103 --> 04:03.551
When you go in to it, you say,
"Hey,

04:03.586 --> 04:05.137
it doesn't make any sense,"
you know?

04:05.172 --> 04:07.827
So it means that
you've really been here.

04:07.862 --> 04:10.241
- It is post-apocalyptic.

04:10.275 --> 04:12.068
It's like
a science fiction film.

04:12.103 --> 04:13.758
What the hell happened here?

04:13.793 --> 04:15.517
- Well, it is post-apocalyptic

04:15.551 --> 04:17.931
except for the fact there's
several hundred thousand

04:17.965 --> 04:19.000
people living here.

04:19.034 --> 04:21.689
[electronic music]

04:21.724 --> 04:23.689
- So the conventional wisdom
seemed to be,

04:23.724 --> 04:24.724
"It's time to
get out of Camden."

04:24.758 --> 04:25.827
Why are you still here?

04:25.862 --> 04:27.517
- Because the need is in Camden.

04:27.551 --> 04:30.172
If every decent person
in Camden leaves Camden,

04:30.206 --> 04:31.724
then we never have a chance.

04:31.758 --> 04:33.517
- You're gonna stay?
- I'm not going anywhere.

04:33.551 --> 04:35.586
My pop-pop didn't leave.
I'm not leaving.

04:35.620 --> 04:37.551
- [laughs]

04:37.586 --> 04:40.000
♪

04:40.034 --> 04:41.517
- This is the only reason
they're gone.

04:41.551 --> 04:43.206
This is the only reason for--

04:43.241 --> 04:45.413
just to protect
my children and my wife.

04:45.448 --> 04:47.758
- 20 years, 30 years...
- Yeah.

04:47.793 --> 04:49.172
- ...will things be better?

04:49.206 --> 04:52.172
- Not 20 years and 30 year.
Hope now.

04:52.206 --> 04:54.827
Next year, thing goes better.

04:54.862 --> 04:57.862
[rapid tapping]

05:02.068 --> 05:07.068
- To me, I really feel
a strong need to forgive...

05:07.103 --> 05:09.724
- Mm-hmm.
- ...and then forget.

05:09.758 --> 05:13.068
And then move on.

05:13.103 --> 05:16.034
- You used to be a tour guide.
- Yes.

05:16.068 --> 05:17.931
- I know you have to
bring people over

05:17.965 --> 05:19.310
to the American War Museum.

05:19.344 --> 05:21.655
In your lifetime,
is there gonna be a time

05:21.689 --> 05:24.310
when that's not
gonna have to be a stop?

05:24.344 --> 05:25.827
No one will remember.

05:25.862 --> 05:27.517
Or should
people always remember?

05:27.551 --> 05:29.551
- I think it's good to remember.

05:29.586 --> 05:34.689
And I think it's good that--
that--

05:34.724 --> 05:38.206
[baby cries]

05:38.241 --> 05:41.517
It's important that
we know about history...

05:41.551 --> 05:44.517
[gentle music]

05:44.551 --> 05:47.034
♪

05:47.068 --> 05:49.344
And to make sure
it's never happen again.

05:49.379 --> 05:52.172
- In conversations that
I had with him, you know,

05:52.206 --> 05:54.034
he'd say,
"Look, I'm not a journalist."

05:54.068 --> 05:57.551
And it's funny because,
you know, I'm a journalist,

05:57.586 --> 06:02.137
and I work with and
live with another journalist

06:02.172 --> 06:03.862
and spend a lot of time
with journalists.

06:03.896 --> 06:08.034
And going and talking to people,
telling stories,

06:08.068 --> 06:13.482
hearing people's stories
that illuminate a place,

06:13.517 --> 06:17.206
if that's not journalism,
I'm really not sure what is.

06:18.517 --> 06:21.655
- How often do you get
to sneak out for a beer?

06:21.689 --> 06:23.172
- Very rarely.
[both chuckle]

06:23.206 --> 06:25.896
First of all, I don't
get to sneak out, period.

06:25.931 --> 06:27.034
[glasses clink]

06:28.551 --> 06:31.862
- The beauty of TV to me is
that it is a cumulative medium.

06:31.896 --> 06:33.655
It's a serialized storytelling.

06:33.689 --> 06:35.172
Every emotional moment

06:35.206 --> 06:39.068
we get to in season four
of a show is earned.

06:39.103 --> 06:41.517
It's built on the back
of everything that came before.

06:41.551 --> 06:42.758
There was
a comfort level there.

06:42.793 --> 06:43.931
We knew each other.

06:43.965 --> 06:45.862
He knew he could push us.

06:45.896 --> 06:47.862
We knew that
he would try to push us.

06:47.896 --> 06:50.206
- People felt like
they knew him.

06:50.241 --> 06:55.034
They felt like if they met him,
he would look out for them.

06:55.068 --> 06:56.241
That sounds weird, but I think

06:56.275 --> 06:57.724
that's how
people felt about him.

06:57.758 --> 06:59.344
They felt like
he was in their corner.

06:59.379 --> 07:01.068
They felt like
he was a force for good.

07:01.103 --> 07:03.137
They felt like his heart
was in the right place.

07:03.172 --> 07:05.689
They felt like he was willing to
stick his neck out for people.

07:05.724 --> 07:08.068
- He was honest about
anything he saw,

07:08.103 --> 07:10.482
not to censor himself

07:10.517 --> 07:12.586
whether positive or negative.

07:12.620 --> 07:14.068
I think that's very important,

07:14.103 --> 07:17.241
and that's why
many people connect,

07:17.275 --> 07:19.206
'cause they see
he's talking about--like,

07:19.241 --> 07:20.931
even the words that
he threw out sometimes.

07:20.965 --> 07:23.758
I was like,
"Jason, can he say that on TV?"

07:23.793 --> 07:26.827
He was like, "Tony can."

07:26.862 --> 07:29.310
- What is the perception
of Mr. Putin these days?

07:29.344 --> 07:31.724
After 14 years, he's in power.

07:31.758 --> 07:33.896
- My--my perception?
- His personal--

07:33.931 --> 07:36.862
- Do you really want to hear it?

07:36.896 --> 07:39.379
- I'm not sure, but let's see.

07:39.413 --> 07:42.551
- A former mid-level manager
in a large corporation.

07:42.586 --> 07:44.758
Short.
I think that's very important.

07:44.793 --> 07:46.241
Short.
- [clears throat]

07:46.275 --> 07:48.586
- Who has found himself
master of the universe.

07:48.620 --> 07:52.000
And like a lot of short people,
if you piss them off,

07:52.034 --> 07:54.724
bad things happen to you.

07:54.758 --> 07:56.068
He likes to
take his shirt off a lot.

07:56.103 --> 07:59.482
- [snickers]
Let's be serious, I mean--

07:59.517 --> 08:02.655
- He strikes me
as a businessman...

08:02.689 --> 08:04.413
- He is.
- A businessman with an ego.

08:04.448 --> 08:07.413
Okay, so he's like Donald Trump,
but shorter.

08:07.448 --> 08:10.827
- Increasingly the show became
about the world around him

08:10.862 --> 08:13.310
and the frame outside of
where he was standing.

08:13.344 --> 08:14.931
And I think
he really understood

08:14.965 --> 08:17.000
the real power in his position

08:17.034 --> 08:19.655
was getting the cameras
to the place in the first place

08:19.689 --> 08:21.241
so that he could
turn them around,

08:21.275 --> 08:23.034
so that he could put the people

08:23.068 --> 08:25.172
who otherwise would never be
on camera on camera,

08:25.206 --> 08:27.000
so he could put
the cultures and the traditions

08:27.034 --> 08:29.482
that have never been seen
before on camera,

08:29.517 --> 08:31.206
so he could show us something,

08:31.241 --> 08:34.172
not just show us
him seeing something.

08:34.206 --> 08:37.310
[gentle string music]

08:37.344 --> 08:39.517
- You have a very
highly educated public here,

08:39.551 --> 08:41.241
one of the most literate
nations on Earth.

08:41.275 --> 08:43.310
- That's funny.
We are highly educated,

08:43.344 --> 08:46.379
like you said, but we're behind

08:46.413 --> 08:49.034
concerning internet
and all that stuff.

08:49.068 --> 08:52.655
Most of us have access
to only the official media,

08:52.689 --> 08:54.068
the official newspaper.

08:54.103 --> 08:56.310
If internet comes,

08:56.344 --> 08:59.310
and I think that government
is trying to delay it,

08:59.344 --> 09:02.241
if that comes,
then I think we change.

09:02.275 --> 09:05.482
People who will have access
to different points of view,

09:05.517 --> 09:08.758
and I don't think
our government wants that.

09:08.793 --> 09:10.137
[soft percussive music]

09:10.172 --> 09:12.000
[egg shell cracks]

09:12.034 --> 09:13.655
- A lot of things happen in
a lot of different

09:13.689 --> 09:16.137
parts of the country
sort of simultaneously.

09:16.172 --> 09:17.482
Kind of amazing that
all of these people

09:17.517 --> 09:19.655
came together very fast.

09:19.689 --> 09:20.862
- How did it happen?
- Yeah.

09:20.896 --> 09:22.137
- Easy. Twitter.

09:22.172 --> 09:23.482
- Twitter?
- Yeah.

09:23.517 --> 09:24.758
- It was really like that?
- Yes.

09:27.448 --> 09:30.172
- Did anyone think it was
possible that in their lifetime

09:30.206 --> 09:31.862
they were gonna see the end
of this son of a...

09:31.896 --> 09:33.931
Most people are telling me
they'd never dream.

09:33.965 --> 09:37.137
- I don't know if you can call
them dreams, hopes, wishes.

09:37.172 --> 09:39.862
It was just
something in the sky,

09:39.896 --> 09:42.034
something I look at every night.
- Right.

09:42.068 --> 09:45.655
- But when I hit that point
and got into Misrata

09:45.689 --> 09:50.379
and stood on Gaddafi's body,
any dream will come true.

09:50.413 --> 09:52.551
- This is a big
oil-rich country.

09:52.586 --> 09:54.413
Why doesn't it look like Dubai?

09:54.448 --> 09:59.000
- Well, I--I hate to be on
this show and talk Niger down--

09:59.034 --> 10:00.827
you know what it is--because

10:00.862 --> 10:03.034
you hear all these things
all the time.

10:03.068 --> 10:06.172
So--so yes, there is corruption.
It is about corruption.

10:06.206 --> 10:09.758
It's about the fact that
the resources that are supposed

10:09.793 --> 10:12.517
to be used for people
aren't being used for people.

10:12.551 --> 10:17.034
Years of military rule meant
that people were brutalized.

10:17.068 --> 10:19.896
There was a fight
against thinking.

10:19.931 --> 10:22.310
Imagine if they were
all well-educated,

10:22.344 --> 10:24.655
if they had access to finance.

10:24.689 --> 10:26.655
I believe
if you're a black person,

10:26.689 --> 10:29.758
whether you're African
or you're African-American,

10:29.793 --> 10:31.655
you're never going to
get any respect

10:31.689 --> 10:35.827
unless there's
a successful black nation.

10:35.862 --> 10:38.000
[pensive music]

10:38.034 --> 10:40.068
- Even if you've been
traveling nearly nonstop

10:40.103 --> 10:42.931
for 15 years like me,
there are places

10:42.965 --> 10:46.068
that snap you out of
your comfortable worldview,

10:46.103 --> 10:48.758
take your assumptions
and your prejudices,

10:48.793 --> 10:50.344
and turn them upside down.

10:50.379 --> 10:52.517
They lead you to believe

10:52.551 --> 10:56.172
that maybe
there is hope in the world.

11:01.620 --> 11:03.275
[upbeat rock music]

11:04.068 --> 11:06.034
- Uh, I eat a lot of meals.

11:06.068 --> 11:10.172
I'm told about 400
per shooting season

11:10.206 --> 11:13.137
um, off and on camera.
[clears throat]

11:13.172 --> 11:16.482
Many of those meals are good.

11:16.517 --> 11:20.034
Many are really bad.

11:20.068 --> 11:26.413
Many are memorable
for reasons good and bad.

11:26.448 --> 11:30.034
A few are epic, truly epic.

11:30.068 --> 11:31.862
They--but they do
come along probably

11:31.896 --> 11:35.068
with more regularity
in my life than yours,

11:35.103 --> 11:37.034
and I will gloat
about that on Instagram

11:37.068 --> 11:38.655
whenever possible, by the way.

11:38.689 --> 11:42.586
[upbeat jazzy music]

11:42.620 --> 11:44.206
- Tony, get closer.

11:44.241 --> 11:45.413
- You are totally
sending me every one

11:45.448 --> 11:46.758
of those pictures by the way.
- Yeah.

11:46.793 --> 11:48.000
- Wow. Look at that.

11:48.034 --> 11:49.724
This style of dish goes back

11:49.758 --> 11:50.724
long before cameras,

11:50.758 --> 11:52.379
but it's perfect.

11:52.413 --> 11:54.068
Is there a more perfect

11:54.103 --> 11:56.758
assortment of
colors and textures?

11:56.793 --> 12:01.068
Everything great about cooking
is encapsulated in this dish.

12:01.103 --> 12:03.000
Often the ugliest dishes are

12:03.034 --> 12:04.758
the ones that are
the most hauntingly delicious.

12:04.793 --> 12:06.758
- Raw blood soup.

12:06.793 --> 12:08.068
- Are we eating out
of an open wound?

12:08.103 --> 12:11.137
- Whole live frogs with garlic.

12:11.172 --> 12:13.655
- That's one of the many
stomach of the cow.

12:13.689 --> 12:18.758
- Alternately unrecognizable,
scorchingly hot, or both.

12:18.793 --> 12:20.344
Well, I'll tell you,
those are some of

12:20.379 --> 12:21.689
the best beans I ever had,
no doubt about it.

12:21.724 --> 12:22.689
- You serious?
- This dude's been everywhere.

12:22.724 --> 12:23.758
- Come on, man.

12:23.793 --> 12:24.758
- There not just delicious.

12:24.793 --> 12:26.206
They're luxurious.

12:26.241 --> 12:28.172
- What can you do
to make it better?

12:28.206 --> 12:30.137
- It's perfect.
There's no improving this dish.

12:30.172 --> 12:33.862
- No. Now nobody talks.
Only we eat.

12:33.896 --> 12:35.896
- Right.
Total silence.

12:35.931 --> 12:38.413
You put far more
on the table than

12:38.448 --> 12:40.724
anyone could conceivably eat.
Is that--

12:40.758 --> 12:43.379
- If you don't like your guest,
you don't put anything.

12:43.413 --> 12:44.586
[laughter]

12:44.620 --> 12:46.172
- Look, I've eaten at a lot of

12:46.206 --> 12:47.931
great restaurants
around the world,

12:47.965 --> 12:49.758
and there was still a little
part of me that was saying,

12:49.793 --> 12:51.482
you know,
"This is gonna be bull--"

12:51.517 --> 12:53.068
- [laughs]

12:53.103 --> 12:55.241
- The guy is out in the field

12:55.275 --> 12:57.413
yanking leaves out
of the ground.

12:57.448 --> 12:59.827
I really didn't expect it
to be as good as it was.

12:59.862 --> 13:01.068
It was delicious.

13:01.103 --> 13:03.379
It was amazingly
delicious for me.

13:03.413 --> 13:05.551
- What's fascinating to me
as somebody who first

13:05.586 --> 13:08.034
knew about Tony
when his first successful book,

13:08.068 --> 13:09.551
"Kitchen Confidential," came out

13:09.586 --> 13:11.862
is I've always
thought of him as a chef

13:11.896 --> 13:13.482
even though it had been years

13:13.517 --> 13:15.034
since he had been
a practicing chef.

13:15.068 --> 13:16.413
You know,
"Kitchen Confidential."

13:16.448 --> 13:18.068
What was the title,
the subtitle?

13:18.103 --> 13:20.344
"Adventures in
the Culinary Underbelly?"

13:20.379 --> 13:22.413
I mean, "underbelly's"
a little bit of a dark word,

13:22.448 --> 13:24.655
but that's sort of
what these--his shows were.

13:24.689 --> 13:27.551
He gave you the full
360-experience of this stuff.

13:27.586 --> 13:29.724
What was its history?
What went in to making it?

13:29.758 --> 13:31.137
What made it great?

13:31.172 --> 13:33.241
And his descriptive powers
were so great

13:33.275 --> 13:36.172
that even though you
as a viewer--

13:36.206 --> 13:39.172
this is the great flaw, I think,
in any food television--

13:39.206 --> 13:42.172
can't taste
what you're watching,

13:42.206 --> 13:45.758
he could convey what
it tasted like or smelled like

13:45.793 --> 13:47.310
or what it evoked in him.

13:47.344 --> 13:49.931
And that, I think,
was kind of the magic of it.

13:49.965 --> 13:53.379
- It was sweet, sweet memories
of this Stegosaurus-sized

13:53.413 --> 13:56.241
shank of cured pork
boiled and boiled

13:56.275 --> 13:58.137
until it literally
falls away from the bone

13:58.172 --> 14:00.206
steaming and moist,
this symphony

14:00.241 --> 14:03.758
of meat and gelatin
and good, good stuff.

14:03.793 --> 14:06.758
God is hiding
in there somewhere.

14:06.793 --> 14:08.931
[upbeat music]

14:08.965 --> 14:13.517
Some things shouldn't change.
I come here to feed my soul.

14:13.551 --> 14:15.758
It's the antidote
to every other place.

14:15.793 --> 14:17.862
♪

14:17.896 --> 14:21.034
Roast bone marrow
with parsley and caper salad.

14:21.068 --> 14:23.896
Thank you.
Yes.

14:23.931 --> 14:25.344
It's a simple good thing,
but it's

14:25.379 --> 14:27.551
one of the most
influential dishes, like,

14:27.586 --> 14:29.310
in the last 20 years.

14:29.344 --> 14:31.034
As I've become older,
I've noticed

14:31.068 --> 14:33.137
the food that I yearn for
is food that

14:33.172 --> 14:35.965
I react to in
an entirely emotional way.

14:37.551 --> 14:41.172
Mmm.
Oh, man.

14:41.206 --> 14:42.413
Wow.

14:42.448 --> 14:44.379
Now, is there an appropriate
way to attack this?

14:44.413 --> 14:45.689
Does one go straight in,
or does one

14:45.724 --> 14:47.068
go at it from an angle?

14:47.103 --> 14:49.310
- It depends
what kind of man you are.

14:49.344 --> 14:51.034
If you're a coward,
you would go from the corner.

14:51.068 --> 14:53.068
- From the corner.
Well, I'm a manly man.

14:53.103 --> 14:55.413
- So you go in the middle.
- All right.

14:57.275 --> 14:59.068
- For somebody
who does what I do,

14:59.103 --> 15:00.931
write about chefs
for people who are chefs,

15:00.965 --> 15:03.655
I think Tony was, like,
as cool as they came, right?

15:03.689 --> 15:05.379
Everyone wanted to--
it was that classic line.

15:05.413 --> 15:07.034
"Everybody wants to be him."

15:07.068 --> 15:08.896
He was a cool guy.
He could write.

15:08.931 --> 15:11.000
He was natural on television.

15:11.034 --> 15:12.689
"The chef swagger,"
that's Tony.

15:12.724 --> 15:14.862
I mean, that started
in some ways with Tony,

15:14.896 --> 15:17.034
or he epitomized that.

15:17.068 --> 15:21.034
Confident, smart,
super computer brain

15:21.068 --> 15:24.931
that could spit out
these incredible witty things.

15:24.965 --> 15:27.689
But he would go
to these places,

15:27.724 --> 15:31.137
and he would evidence, I think,
an incredible humility.

15:31.172 --> 15:33.241
He was genuinely curious.

15:33.275 --> 15:35.344
He wasn't trying to teach them.

15:35.379 --> 15:37.724
He wasn't trying to show off.

15:37.758 --> 15:41.034
- How long does that broth
have to simmer to get good?

15:41.068 --> 15:43.206
- An hour.
- Wow. Really?

15:43.241 --> 15:46.241
I would've guessed,
like, 14 hours.

15:46.275 --> 15:48.724
I want to see how much
you put in there.

15:48.758 --> 15:51.724
- You got to make it look
really red in there.

15:51.758 --> 15:53.517
That should be blood red.

15:53.551 --> 15:58.379
- Nice burning feeling
on my lips, flop sweat, happy.

15:58.413 --> 15:59.931
People are put on Earth
for various purposes.

15:59.965 --> 16:03.379
I was put on Earth to do this,
eat noodles right here.

16:05.517 --> 16:07.413
At the end of a long night,

16:07.448 --> 16:10.689
decisions good and bad,
friends old and new,

16:10.724 --> 16:13.896
a night spent playing
or a night spent working,

16:13.931 --> 16:17.827
all across the world wherever cooks stumble out of work late,

16:17.862 --> 16:19.862
there's a place like this.

16:19.896 --> 16:22.068
Gentlemen.
- Hey, Tony.

16:22.103 --> 16:23.862
- How are you?
- Nice to see you again.

16:23.896 --> 16:25.310
- Good to see you. What's up?
- Nice to see you again.

16:25.344 --> 16:26.379
- It's the city
that never sleeps.

16:26.413 --> 16:28.034
24-hour Mokatal, right?

16:28.068 --> 16:31.034
- This place is very democratic
'cause, like,

16:31.068 --> 16:32.827
everybody comes late at night,

16:32.862 --> 16:37.482
taxi drivers, hookers,
and cooks, because we can be--

16:37.517 --> 16:39.413
- Yeah. Why is it that
hookers and cooks always, like,

16:39.448 --> 16:41.137
are welcome at the same place,
you know?

16:41.172 --> 16:44.344
Where--the--
the same social standard.

16:44.379 --> 16:45.827
I'm ready, man.
I am hungry.

16:45.862 --> 16:47.137
I have had nothing
to eat all day.

16:47.172 --> 16:49.034
- Yeah?
- I am starving.

16:49.068 --> 16:51.655
[wondrous musical flourish]

16:51.689 --> 16:53.689
[indistinct chatter]

16:53.724 --> 16:58.206
- I think Tony's appreciation
for sort of the rank-and-file

16:58.241 --> 17:01.413
members of a kitchen team
was always there.

17:01.448 --> 17:05.206
It was something that I think
he felt very profoundly.

17:05.241 --> 17:09.758
I think what he took
from that profession was

17:09.793 --> 17:14.724
a real curiosity and
a sincere love of food.

17:14.758 --> 17:16.862
You know,
somebody once said to me,

17:16.896 --> 17:18.896
"Great food is an adventure,"

17:18.931 --> 17:22.172
and I think that's
where the beginnings

17:22.206 --> 17:24.655
of what he
transitioned into came from.

17:24.689 --> 17:26.413
- I mean,
if you don't like food,

17:26.448 --> 17:28.413
if you're not
interested in food,

17:28.448 --> 17:31.862
it's--it's really a problem.

17:31.896 --> 17:34.206
It's a relationship non-starter.

17:34.241 --> 17:36.172
It's like someone saying,
"I don't like music."

17:36.206 --> 17:40.758
You know,
conversation's kind of over.

17:40.793 --> 17:43.517
But I mean, I'll always look
at the world from that per--

17:43.551 --> 17:47.379
I mean, all--all my values,
every important skill,

17:47.413 --> 17:51.068
any good things
about my character,

17:51.103 --> 17:54.206
any good characteristics
I have,

17:54.241 --> 17:55.827
all the important
lessons of my life

17:55.862 --> 17:57.931
I learned as a dishwasher
or as a cook.

17:57.965 --> 18:00.758
And I'm always gonna look at
the world through that prism.

18:06.103 --> 18:07.965
[upbeat rock music]

18:08.758 --> 18:11.000
[stirring piano music]

18:11.034 --> 18:13.241
- A few years back,
I got the words

18:13.275 --> 18:17.000
"I am certain of nothing"
tattooed on my arm.

18:17.034 --> 18:20.862
It's what makes travel
what it is:

18:20.896 --> 18:22.517
an endless learning curve.

18:22.551 --> 18:25.482
Well, it's a popular metaphor
for India-Pakistan is

18:25.517 --> 18:27.241
"Twins separated at birth."

18:27.275 --> 18:28.896
- We were never twins, I mean--

18:28.931 --> 18:30.482
- One.
- It was one country.

18:30.517 --> 18:31.931
You could say dismembered.
- Right.

18:31.965 --> 18:33.482
- You know, if you
cut a body in two,

18:33.517 --> 18:35.206
they're not gonna become twins.

18:35.241 --> 18:38.310
- The joy of being wrong,
of being confused.

18:38.344 --> 18:40.586
Critics of the government,
critics of Putin,

18:40.620 --> 18:42.896
bad things
seem to happen to them.

18:42.931 --> 18:46.724
- Yes. Unfortunately
existing power represent,

18:46.758 --> 18:50.310
let I say,
Russia of 19th century.

18:50.344 --> 18:53.206
- You could kill a journalist
and get away with it.

18:53.241 --> 18:56.896
Why are you still here?
- It's my choice.

18:56.931 --> 18:59.379
My choice is fight.

18:59.413 --> 19:01.034
I really believe that

19:01.068 --> 19:05.344
good journalists
can change the world.

19:05.379 --> 19:08.034
- At first you see what you see in so many places,

19:08.068 --> 19:10.689
busy markets,

19:10.724 --> 19:13.034
the noisy streets.

19:13.068 --> 19:15.068
But look just
a little bit longer,

19:15.103 --> 19:17.758
a little bit deeper,
and you'll see

19:17.793 --> 19:21.551
it's not so different

19:21.586 --> 19:23.034
here from anywhere really.

19:23.068 --> 19:28.172
♪

19:29.517 --> 19:33.034
- It's incredible thinking back
how fearless he was.

19:33.068 --> 19:35.862
You know, he went to CNN,
which is a network that

19:35.896 --> 19:38.034
travels all over the world
and goes in to war zones,

19:38.068 --> 19:40.000
and he saw that,
I think, as a challenge.

19:40.034 --> 19:43.551
And he was not afraid
to ask uncomfortable questions,

19:43.586 --> 19:47.172
go to uncomfortable places,
poke at uncomfortable scabs.

19:47.206 --> 19:50.241
That's kind of amazing,
you know, to--to--

19:50.275 --> 19:53.000
as you grow
more comfortable in station

19:53.034 --> 19:57.344
to become more eager to
engage in uncomfortable truths

19:57.379 --> 20:00.344
and uncomfortable situations
and uncomfortable questions.

20:00.379 --> 20:02.482
You would think it would go
in the opposite direction,

20:02.517 --> 20:04.000
but with Tony it never did.

20:04.724 --> 20:06.482
[rousing guitar music]

20:06.517 --> 20:09.206
- Iran. Finally.

20:09.241 --> 20:12.931
I've been trying to get in this country five years now.

20:12.965 --> 20:17.931
It's been the big blank spot
on my things-to-do list.

20:17.965 --> 20:25.172
♪

20:32.379 --> 20:37.413
The Iran I've seen on TV
and read about in the papers,

20:37.448 --> 20:41.068
it's a much bigger picture.

20:41.103 --> 20:45.655
Let's put it this way,
it's complicated,

20:45.689 --> 20:49.724
And I think it's
gonna shock the hell out of you.

21:03.620 --> 21:05.034
- People couldn't believe it.

21:05.068 --> 21:08.206
Iranians in Iran
and Iranian-Americans

21:08.241 --> 21:11.379
were genuinely really
happy and appreciative

21:11.413 --> 21:14.241
that he would come
and do this show there.

21:14.275 --> 21:18.068
In a place like Iran
where visitors from abroad,

21:18.103 --> 21:20.034
and especially
visitors from America,

21:20.068 --> 21:22.758
are few and far between,
it matters.

21:22.793 --> 21:23.758
[string music]

21:23.793 --> 21:25.310
- As print journalists,

21:25.344 --> 21:26.482
our job's difficult,

21:26.517 --> 21:27.758
but it's also kind of easy,

21:27.793 --> 21:30.344
'cause there's so much
to write about.

21:30.379 --> 21:32.896
You know, it's--the
difficult part is convincing

21:32.931 --> 21:34.931
people on the other side
of the world that

21:34.965 --> 21:38.310
what we're telling you we're
seeing in front of our eyes

21:38.344 --> 21:39.344
is actually there.

21:39.379 --> 21:40.689
When you walk down the street,

21:40.724 --> 21:42.758
you see
a different side of things.

21:42.793 --> 21:45.896
People are proud.
The culture is vibrant.

21:45.931 --> 21:48.241
People have a lot to say.

21:48.275 --> 21:50.482
- Jason Rezaian is
"The Washington Post's"

21:50.517 --> 21:52.310
correspondent for Iran.

21:52.344 --> 21:54.482
Yeganeh, his wife
and a fellow journalist,

21:54.517 --> 21:57.896
works for the UAE-based
newspaper "The National."

21:57.931 --> 22:00.034
Jason is Iranian-American.

22:00.068 --> 22:03.482
Yeganeh is
a full Iranian citizen.

22:03.517 --> 22:06.137
This is their city, Tehran.

22:06.172 --> 22:08.379
The official attitude
towards fun in general

22:08.413 --> 22:11.586
seems to be ever-shifting.

22:11.620 --> 22:14.206
How--
is fun even a good idea?

22:14.241 --> 22:17.068
- There's a lot of security.
There's lots of rules.

22:17.103 --> 22:23.241
There are a lot of people
in place to make sure

22:23.275 --> 22:25.655
you do the right thing
and not do the wrong thing.

22:25.689 --> 22:28.344
But there's a lot of
push and pull,

22:28.379 --> 22:29.896
a lot of give and take.

22:29.931 --> 22:32.172
When I first started
coming here, you wouldn't hear

22:32.206 --> 22:35.241
pop music in a restaurant or...
- Right.

22:35.275 --> 22:36.724
- It's everywhere now.
- Now it's everywhere.

22:36.758 --> 22:38.344
- We have police.

22:38.379 --> 22:42.379
They arrest girls or women
for having bad hijab

22:42.413 --> 22:46.241
or not being covered enough,
but it's not that we live

22:46.275 --> 22:48.724
with the police in our head,
you know?

22:48.758 --> 22:50.413
[gentle music]

22:50.448 --> 22:54.862
♪

23:07.275 --> 23:10.344
- I brought up the experience
of being on a show

23:10.379 --> 23:14.241
just a few weeks
previous to--to our arrest.

23:14.275 --> 23:17.172
And I said, "Look, you know,
this thing is coming.

23:17.206 --> 23:19.758
It's not gonna play out
well for you."

23:19.793 --> 23:21.758
- At some point
towards the end,

23:21.793 --> 23:23.379
my interrogator
brought a picture.

23:23.413 --> 23:26.172
"Who is this guy?
Is he your dad or his dad?"

23:26.206 --> 23:29.413
I was like, "No.
You really don't know him?"

23:29.448 --> 23:30.931
And he was like, "No."

23:30.965 --> 23:34.172
I said, "Well,
this is a very famous guy.

23:34.206 --> 23:36.931
If you are interested
in traveling, food, dah-dah-dah,

23:36.965 --> 23:38.068
you should watch his show."

23:38.103 --> 23:40.172
But he told me,
"There was nothing

23:40.206 --> 23:42.482
in your conversation
with him about food."

23:42.517 --> 23:46.172
I was like, "No, we discussed
a little bit of rice and fish

23:46.206 --> 23:49.379
"and things like that,
but it was mostly

23:49.413 --> 23:53.241
cultural topics,
social life, things like that."

23:53.275 --> 23:58.034
And he said, "So it's gonna be
another punch in our face?"

23:58.068 --> 23:59.896
I was like, "No, no, no.
It's not gonna be like that.

23:59.931 --> 24:01.482
"He's not that kind of guy.

24:01.517 --> 24:05.034
He's gonna tell the truth
no matter what it is."

24:05.068 --> 24:06.931
And interestingly, I remember

24:06.965 --> 24:09.000
I told them about
one discussion

24:09.034 --> 24:10.517
we had with Tony,
'cause at some point

24:10.551 --> 24:13.551
we talked about
the situation of women in Iran.

24:13.586 --> 24:16.586
[upbeat music]

24:16.620 --> 24:19.241
- You know, one of the first
things that people will say

24:19.275 --> 24:20.413
when you say,
"Well, I'm going to Iran."

24:20.448 --> 24:22.206
"Oh, yeah, but
don't they make women

24:22.241 --> 24:24.827
do this, this, and this?"
- Yeah.

24:24.862 --> 24:27.862
- Actually... not so much.

24:27.896 --> 24:29.206
- Yeah.
- Not as much as our...

24:29.241 --> 24:30.724
- Friends. Yeah.
- ...friends.

24:30.758 --> 24:32.413
- Compare and contrast.

24:32.448 --> 24:35.137
women aren't allowed
to drive in Saudi Arabia.

24:35.172 --> 24:37.241
- That's right. Or vote.
- Or vote.

24:37.275 --> 24:39.482
- You can drive. You can vote.
- Yeah, of course.

24:39.517 --> 24:42.172
- Can you own a business?
- Of course.

24:42.206 --> 24:45.758
My sister is an accountant.
She has her own company.

24:45.793 --> 24:50.344
Girls are allowed to do almost
everything, uh, except

24:50.379 --> 24:52.344
we want to go and watch football
which is like--

24:52.379 --> 24:54.689
- Can't go watch football?
- We cannot.

24:54.724 --> 24:57.931
- Women's issues are often
at the spear point of change

24:57.965 --> 24:59.724
or possible change here.

24:59.758 --> 25:02.206
On one hand, prevailing
conservative attitudes

25:02.241 --> 25:04.344
demand certain things.

25:04.379 --> 25:07.137
On the other hand,
Iranian women are

25:07.172 --> 25:09.689
famously assertive,
opinionated.

25:09.724 --> 25:11.241
It's a striking difference from

25:11.275 --> 25:13.241
almost everywhere else
in the region.

25:13.275 --> 25:15.379
So why are we so friendly
with the Saudis again?

25:15.413 --> 25:19.551
- That's a great question.
It's a really good question.

25:19.586 --> 25:21.517
- I'm happy that
you asked that question.

25:21.551 --> 25:23.172
[laughs]

25:23.206 --> 25:27.241
[percussive musical flourish]

25:27.275 --> 25:30.241
And I sort of, like, told
the story to my interrogator.

25:30.275 --> 25:33.862
It was like, "Okay, sounds
like a good conversation.

25:33.896 --> 25:37.344
So he--he likes us?"

25:37.379 --> 25:40.241
I was like, "He likes Iranians.
He likes Iran."

25:40.275 --> 25:43.034
So that was kind of convincing.

25:43.068 --> 25:48.034
I was able to
cool things off finally...

25:48.068 --> 25:50.000
[rousing electronic music]

25:50.034 --> 25:51.758
- Do you like it?
You happy here?

25:51.793 --> 25:54.137
- Look, I--I love it,

25:54.172 --> 25:56.724
and I hate it,
you know, but it's home.

25:56.758 --> 25:58.068
It's become home.

25:58.103 --> 26:01.310
- Are you optimistic
about the future?

26:01.344 --> 26:03.862
- Yeah.
Especially if this nuclear deal

26:03.896 --> 26:07.827
finally happens, uh, yeah.

26:07.862 --> 26:09.310
Very much actually.

26:09.344 --> 26:11.241
- Let's assume the worst.

26:11.275 --> 26:14.517
Let's assume that you cannot
see any way to reconcile

26:14.551 --> 26:18.172
what you think of Iran with your own personal beliefs,

26:18.206 --> 26:20.413
that you just
generally don't approve.

26:20.448 --> 26:22.068
- Yeah.
- I think those are exactly

26:22.103 --> 26:24.000
the sort of places
you should go.

26:24.034 --> 26:25.137
- Totally.

26:25.172 --> 26:26.551
- See who we're talking about

26:26.586 --> 26:28.000
and where we're
talking about here.

26:28.034 --> 26:30.034
- I think it's
almost un-American

26:30.068 --> 26:32.655
not to go to those places,
you know?

26:32.689 --> 26:34.724
♪

26:34.758 --> 26:36.655
- I don't know that I can put
it in any kind of perspective.

26:36.689 --> 26:39.034
I feel the, you know,
deeply conflicting,

26:39.068 --> 26:41.724
deeply confusing,
exhilarating,

26:41.758 --> 26:44.517
heartbreaking,
beautiful place.

26:44.551 --> 26:47.379
- Yeah, exactly.

26:47.413 --> 26:49.862
[laughter]

26:49.896 --> 26:53.206
[indistinct chatter]
[camera shutter clicks]

26:56.689 --> 26:58.758
[upbeat rock music]

26:59.931 --> 27:00.931
- When putting together
a list of where

27:00.965 --> 27:03.655
we're going on any given year,

27:03.689 --> 27:06.482
there's a really
unhealthy fascination

27:06.517 --> 27:10.689
with my relationship
with plumbing, shall we say.

27:10.724 --> 27:12.689
So basically if
I'm going without a crapper

27:12.724 --> 27:15.034
for extended periods of time
on one show,

27:15.068 --> 27:16.758
the next show's
pretty much gonna be some place

27:16.793 --> 27:20.586
with good hot-water pressure
and, you know,

27:20.620 --> 27:23.172
a degree of flush toilets that

27:23.206 --> 27:26.517
even the most skeptical
and cranky person

27:26.551 --> 27:28.551
would find curiously pleasing.

27:28.586 --> 27:30.655
[light music]

27:30.689 --> 27:32.068
I never had any dreams of

27:32.103 --> 27:34.000
growing up
in socialist wonderland.

27:34.034 --> 27:36.344
Like, when I was a brief period where I was a hippie,

27:36.379 --> 27:39.586
the idea of living in a commune,
not attractive to me.

27:39.620 --> 27:42.344
- I was born in a communal flat
with three other families

27:42.379 --> 27:45.034
sharing one john, one kitchen.
- No way.

27:45.068 --> 27:46.862
- They would feed me
when I had no food.

27:46.896 --> 27:49.413
- No way.
I share my toilet with no man.

27:49.448 --> 27:53.931
- [jazzy vocalizing]

27:53.965 --> 27:57.068
♪

27:57.103 --> 27:59.413
- Well, I'm looking forward
to the week.

